did.abstract: This collection contains the records of the Tufts Daily.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized into five series: Photographs; Negatives; Slides; 2018 accessions; and Production Files.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Tufts Daily, founded in 1980, is the daily undergraduate student newspaper for Tufts University. Its mission is to provide a source of news for the Tufts community, a forum for the exchange of ideas, and a means for students to gain experience in journalism. It covers university news, sports, and events as well as some national and international news. It also includes editorials, a calendar of events, and syndicated comics. Published and distributed free of charge on class days during the academic year, the Tufts Daily is student-run and receives no financial support from Tufts University.
Particularly valuable are the Tufts Daily photographs documenting campus life - the people, places, events, and activities of Tufts University.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: During processing every effort was made to maintain the original order and file titles kept by the Daily staff. Where it was impossible to ascertain original order and title, this was noted in the item level description.

The photographic prints were put into folders. Most negatives were originally housed in binders. Some negatives were crumpled and damaged due to long term exposure to moisture. Negatives were transferred to archival quality sleeves and stored in drop front boxes so as to flatten the negatives. The slides were re-housed in archival slide boxes. Random items, such as light bulbs and musical discs, which accompanied the collection, were weeded.

2018 accessions were processed by Leah Edelman and Alejandra Garcia in 2018. Photographs and negatives were placed in archival boxes and folders. Received order was maintained where possible. Photographs on CD-R were transferred to a stabilization queue for the Digital Archivist. A box-level inventory and series-level description were created and the finding aid was updated at the time of processing.

Photographs and production files on CD-Rs were stabilized in 2018 -- 2019 by Rose Koven using Bagger. The extracted files were processed in 2020 -- 2021 by Records and Accessioning Archivist Jane Kelly. Duplicate files and low-resolution copies of photographs were deleted. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing. Files were copied to Box for access by Jane Kelly and Archives and Research Assistant Cassandra Anderson. Please note that files were not converted for access and all may not be viewable in Box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection includes photographic prints, negatives, slides, CD-Rs, and photograph and production files extracted from CD-R disks once used in the production of the Tufts Daily newspaper. It also contains documents, such as information sheets for the negatives, contact sheets, and office documentation. The predominant file formats in this collection include the following, in order of prevalence: Exif, TIFF, JPEG, Microsoft Word documents, plain text files, PDF, and QuarkXPress documents.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Some material in this collection may be protected by copyright and other rights. Please see "Reproductions and Use" on the Digital Collections and Archives website for more information about reproductions and permission to publish. The Tufts Daily transfers to the Tufts University Digital Collections and Archives legal title, copyright, and literary property rights of the photographic prints and negatives it transfers to the Tufts University Digital Collections and Archives in as far as the Tufts Daily holds those rights and title. Digital Collections and Archives agrees that the Tufts Daily shall retain the right to reproduce and/or publish the images in the collection for its own purposes. In granting permission to third parties to publish images from the collection, the DCA will request that the photographer's name, if known, be included in the credit line for each image so used in addition to the Tufts Daily's name and the DCA collection number. In cases where the photographer is unknown, images will be credited with the Tufts Daily's name and the DCA collection number. The Tufts Daily agrees that Digital Collections and Archives has the responsibility for the final disposition of any and all material in this gift.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is in the original order kept by the Daily staff. One portion is arranged alphabetically by person, organization, or place, and one portion is arranged alphabetically into categories by subject/sport. Digital material extracted from CD-Rs and processed in 2020 -- 2021 is arranged in chronological order. Original order has been maintained for all files.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Digital material in this series that was originally on CD-Rs was stabilized in 2018 -- 2019 by Rose Koven using Bagger. The extracted files were processed in 2020 -- 2021 by Records and Accessioning Archivist Jane Kelly. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing. Files were copied to Box for access by Jane Kelly and Archives and Research Assistant Cassandra Anderson. Duplicate and near-duplicate files were identified and were not copied to Box for access. Near-duplicate files include both low-resolution copies of photographs and thumbnails; high-resolution versions were retained. Please note that files were not converted for access and all may not be viewable in Box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains negatives produced by the Tufts Daily between 1980 and 2004. Series may include information sheets for the negatives, contact sheets, and Tufts Daily office documentation.

Negatives are arranged chronologically by semester or academic year. Each folder contains negatives from one binder. Binders were generally labeled and dated and that information was retained. Undated binders were placed at the end of the series based on apparent dates. When dating individual negative sheets, the date on negative sheet took precedence over binder label. Descriptive titles [] replaced non-descriptive binder titles, such as "Requisitions" and "Negative to be picked up by", and were added to un-labeled binders. The original, non-descriptive titles appear in the Notes field. Subjects include news, events, sports, feature stories, students, faculty, and campus facilities.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged chronologically by semester or academic year.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: All material in this series was originally on CD-Rs, which were stabilized in 2018 -- 2019 by Rose Koven using Bagger. The extracted files were processed in 2020 -- 2021 by Records and Accessioning Archivist Jane Kelly. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing. Files were copied to Box for access by Jane Kelly and Archives and Research Assistant Cassandra Anderson. Please note that files were not converted for access and all may not be viewable in Box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains production files extracted from CD-Rs that were created by Tufts Daily staff between 2001 and 2004. The bulk of the material consists of the production files from a selection of issues from September and December 2004. There are files from each section of the newspaper, including the Arts, Comics, Editorial, Features, News, Sports, Viewpoints, and Wires sections. These files consist of the individual text and image files for articles, as well as PDF and layout files for each page. The remaining material consists of files created by a former photography editor, Justin Golub, and includes guidelines for photography work, meeting notes, and proposals. The predominant file formats in this series include the following, in order of prevalence: Word documents, plain text documents, PDF, TIFF, JPG, and QuarkXPress documents.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Transferred by Ryan Shaffer, former Editor-in-Chief of the Tufts Daily, 2020 -- 2021, accessions UA-2021-032 and UA-2021-044.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged alphabetically by podcast title.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This series was processed by Records and Accessioning Archivist, Jane Kelly, in May 2021. Materials were bagged using Bagger and ingested to the Tufts Digital Library. A file-level inventory was created, and series and collection-level description were updated at the time of processing. Digital files in this series were transferred to Box and their original creation dates were no longer retrievable. Circa dates have been assigned based on the air date of the episode if an exact date could not be determined.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains podcats and scripts created by the Tufts Daily, including from the programs A Blight on the Hill, The Rewind, and Take Town, as well as a production schedule. The material dates from 2019 to 2021. Item-level description of individual podcast episodes is from the Tufts Daily account on Spotify, the audio streaming service.

did.unittitle: Episode 3: The Green Line Extension script

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: In the third episode of A Blight on the Hill, reporters Rachel Carp, Abigail Fisch, Elie Levine, and Julia Greco talk to experts and investigate all aspects of the Green Line Extension's expected move to Medford, including housing, displacement and rising rents.

did.unittitle: Episode one: Tufts strikes for climate; swastika posted on door

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: In the first-ever episode of The Rewind, Tufts students protest the complicity of Tufts and the state of Massachusetts in the climate crisis. A Jewish student finds a swastika affixed to their door, another incident of Antisemitism and white supremacy on the Tufts campus. Guests: Connor Dale and Austin Clementi.

did.unittitle: Episode three: student finds homophobic slur scratched into door

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Producer Tim Leong talks to reporter Alexander Thompson about the homophobic slur scratched into a Tufts student's door, marking the second incident of hate on campus this month.

did.unittitle: Episode four: African American exhibit defaced, bias response teams announced

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Producer Stephanie Rifkin speaks to reporter Robert Kaplan about the defacement of a sign in the African American Trail Project exhibit, and the subsequent creation of two Bias Response Teams.

did.unittitle: Episode five: Medford City Council requests Tufts' master plans

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Host Arlo Moore-Bloom talks to reporter Elie Levine about Medford's request for Tufts' institutional master plans, which would reveal future development plans for approximately the next ten years.

did.unittitle: Final episode: Tufts faculty donate overwhelmingly to Democrats

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Host Arlo Moore-Bloom talks to reporters Anton Shenk and Caleb Symons about their latest investigation on faculty donations to political organizations. Shenk and Symons found that ninety-four percent of donated money went to Democratic candidates and causes, while just under 1% went to Republican-aligned recipients.

did.unittitle: Episode one: Tufts begins review of fossil fuel investment

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: In this semester's first episode of The Rewind, host Leslie Gladstone interviews reporter Connor Dale and Tufts Climate Action representative Hanna Carr about the school's effort to review investments in its endowment.

did.unittitle: Episode 2: climate conversations: Tufts' ban on direct coal investments and winter weather trends

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On this episode of "The Rewind," we explore Tufts' Feb. 10 commitment to ban direct investment in coal and tar sands with Tufts Daily reporter Alicia Zou and Tufts Climate Action representative Grace Abe. We continue our climate discussion as The Rewind's Ty Blitstein talks with Daily reporters Katie Furey and Keira Myles about the winter weather. Stay tuned weekly for more stories from the Tufts Daily.

did.unittitle: Episode 3: stories on the hill: equity and inclusion report, RA demands, and remote first-year experiences

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On today's episode, we talk with Michael Weiskopf, a news reporter at the Tufts Daily, about the recently released report from the university's Equity and Inclusion workstream, launched as part of its efforts to become an anti-racist institution. Additionally, Silvia Wang reports on residential assistants' demands for higher compensation and improved communication with the administration, and Nicole Garay speaks with remote first-year students about their Tufts experiences.

did.unittitle: Episode 4: education on campus: Tufts applications, pedagogical partnership program, and Tisch College research

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On today's episode, we hear from Jack Maniaci about Tufts' early decision applications, and we share an update on the Pedagogical Partnership Program, which pairs students with faculty to promote equity and enhance academic experiences. We also dive further into education, discussing Tisch College's research on the state of civic education in Massachusetts and at the national level.

did.unittitle: Episode 5: looking to the future: university vaccinations, recycling smart on campus, and pandemic study abroad

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On this Rewind episode, Governor Charlie Baker announced Wednesday that vaccines will be available to Massachusetts residents 16 and older on April 19; what does that mean for when and how Tufts students can be vaccinated? Also, we discuss a Green Fund project aimed at improving recycling habits on campus and how students are adjusting their plans to study abroad amid the pandemic.

did.unittitle: Episode 6: supporting the community: spirituality, social justice, and Medford's finances

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: On today's episode, Rewind Reporter Ty Blitstein shares his conversations with the University Chaplaincy about its deepening focus on social justice and its upcoming Russell Lecture on Spiritual Life. Delivering the lecture is Reverend Adam Russell Taylor, President of Sojourners, a nonprofit that aims to integrate faith with social justice. More on that later in today's episode. We also host a discussion with Jack Hirsch about the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the City of Medford's finances.

did.unittitle: Episode 7: tour of Campus: week's news, lights, and history of Tufts' buildings

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Tour of Campus: Week's news, lights, and history of Tufts' buildings by The Tufts Daily

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: In Episode 1 of Take Town, the only Tufts Daily sports podcast that matters or exists, Sam Weidner and Aiden Herrod discuss the storied legacy of Kobe Bryant and its more complicated aspects.

did.unittitle: Episode two: students, NFL: welcome back!

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Take Town is BACK for season 2! Aiden and Matt talk about the Fall return to sports, what this NFL season is going to look like, and explore what the heck this strange, strange time means for professional sports. Join us!

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Aiden and Matt break down the NBA Finals and other hardcourt matters.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: After another ring for Team Bron, Aiden and Matt are left with no other choice for this week's episode. That's right, Goat Talk. Also, a very special guest sits in. Join us!
